    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Roadside Shrines</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Ana Del Campo letter on Nicole Krauss's June 18 travel article on Greece notes mailbox-like shrines along roadways are put there to honor people who died in car accidents (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor: In her enjoyable article ''Where the Gods Are Neighbors'' (June 18), Nicole Krauss writes about the mountain roads by which ''at every switchback turn, a small, mailbox-like shrine with faded icon, biscuits and half-empty bottle of Fanta seemed placed to ensure safe passage.'' If only!</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor: In her enjoyable article ''Where the Gods Are Neighbors'' (June 18), Nicole Krauss writes about the mountain roads by which ''at every switchback turn, a small, mailbox-like shrine with faded icon, biscuits and half-empty bottle of Fanta seemed placed to ensure safe passage.'' If only!</p>
        <p>My grandmother, mother and I went to Greece in 1997 and saw Epidaurus, Olympia and Mycenae with a tour group, and spent several days in Athens. As we traveled over those narrow, winding roads through the mountains, our guide told us that those shrines were in honor of people who had died in car accidents. Apparently, the families of victims sometimes maintain such shrines for a few years.</p>
        <p>ANA DEL CAMPO  North Bergen, N.J.</p>
      </block>
